  "response": "Let's analyze the reasons why the bond angle of Sulfur dioxide (SO2) is greater than that of Ozone (O3):\n\n1. Electronic Structure:\n- SO2: Central sulfur atom has 6 valence electrons\n- O3: Central oxygen atom has 6 valence electrons\n\n2. Electron Pair Arrangement:\n- SO2: Central sulfur has 2 bonding pairs and 1 lone pair\n- O3: Central oxygen has 1 lone pair and 2 bonding pairs\n\n3. Electron Pair Repulsion:\n- According to VSEPR theory, lone pairs require more space than bonding pairs\n- Lone pairs exert greater repulsive forces on bonding pairs\n\n4. Bond Angle Comparison:\n- SO2 bond angle: approximately 119\u00b0\n- O3 bond angle: approximately 116.5\u00b0\n\n5. Reason for Larger Bond Angle in SO2:\n- The lone pair in sulfur dioxide is less sterically hindering\n- Less electron pair repulsion allows for a slightly wider bond angle\n- Larger atomic size of sulfur compared to oxygen also contributes\n\nThe difference in bond angles results from the varying electron pair arrangements and repulsive forces in these molecules.",
